WEBVTT

1
00:01:08.820 --> 00:01:12.657
<i>This is a true story about
friendship that runs deeper than blood.</i>

2
00:01:13.575 --> 00:01:18.079
<i>This is my story and that of the only three
friends in my life who truly mattered.</i>

3
00:01:19.038 --> 00:01:23.167
<i>Two of them were killers
who never made it past the age of 30.</i>

4
00:01:23.376 --> 00:01:27.046
<i>The other is a non-practicing attorney
living with the pain of his past…</i>

5
00:01:27.213 --> 00:01:30.550
<i>… too afraid to let it go,
never confronting its horror.</i>

6
00:01:32.343 --> 00:01:37.056
<i>I'm the only one who could speak for them
and the children we were.</i>

7
00:03:17.490 --> 00:03:19.784
<i>My three friends and I were inseparable.</i>

8
00:03:19.951 --> 00:03:22.870
<i>Happy and content to live
in the closed world of Hell's Kitchen.</i>

9
00:03:23.037 --> 00:03:26.124
<i>The West Side streets of Manhattan
were our private playground…</i>

10
00:03:26.290 --> 00:03:31.462
<i>… a cement kingdom where we felt ourselves
to be nothing less than absolute rulers.</i>

11
00:03:33.047 --> 00:03:35.925
<i>Hell's Kitchen was populated by
an uneasy blend of Irish…</i>

12
00:03:36.092 --> 00:03:39.095
<i>… Italian, Puerto Rican
and Eastern European laborers.</i>

13
00:03:39.262 --> 00:03:41.806
<i>Hard men living hard lives.</i>

14
00:03:51.399 --> 00:03:54.652
<i>We lived in railroad apartments
inside red brick tenements.</i>

15
00:03:54.819 --> 00:03:58.156
<i>Few mothers worked and all had trouble
with the men they married.</i>

16
00:04:03.953 --> 00:04:08.166
Shut the fuck up! I buried one fucking wife,
I could bury another one.

17
00:04:13.379 --> 00:04:16.507
<i>Domestic violence
was a cottage industry in Hell's Kitchen.</i>

18
00:04:16.674 --> 00:04:19.343
<i>Yet there was no divorce
and few separations.</i>

19
00:04:19.510 --> 00:04:21.554
<i>The will of the Church was forceful.</i>

20
00:04:21.721 --> 00:04:25.224
<i>For a marriage to end,
someone usually had to die.</i>

21
00:04:27.685 --> 00:04:29.604
<i>Yet despite the harshness of life…</i>

22
00:04:29.771 --> 00:04:32.774
<i>… Hell's Kitchen offered the kids
on its streets a safety net…</i>

23
00:04:32.940 --> 00:04:35.234
<i>… enjoyed by few other neighborhoods.</i>

24
00:04:35.777 --> 00:04:38.946
<i>Crimes against people of the neighborhood
were not permitted.</i>

25
00:04:39.322 --> 00:04:42.033
<i>When they did occur,
the punishment doled out was severe…</i>

26
00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:44.368
<i>… and in some cases, final.</i>

27
00:04:44.535 --> 00:04:48.039
<i>A drug dealer from an uptown neighborhood
moved heroin into Hell's Kitchen.</i>

28
00:04:48.206 --> 00:04:51.375
<i>A packet killed the 12-year-old son
of a Puerto Rican numbers runner.</i>

29
00:04:51.542 --> 00:04:54.712
<i>It was the last packet
the dealer ever sold.</i>

30
00:04:55.546 --> 00:04:59.842
<i>Hell's Kitchen was a place of innocence
ruled by corruption.</i>

31
00:05:01.469 --> 00:05:04.430
<i>My friends and I spent lots of time
inside Holy Angels.</i>

32
00:05:04.597 --> 00:05:06.682
<i>We each served as altar boys.</i>

33
00:05:06.849 --> 00:05:10.895
<i>Everyone wanted to work funeral masses
since the funeral included a $3 fee…</i>

34
00:05:11.062 --> 00:05:13.898
<i>… and more if you looked
sufficiently somber.</i>

35
00:05:15.149 --> 00:05:19.487
<i>There was competition between the four of us
to come up with the best and boldest prank.</i>

36
00:05:20.571 --> 00:05:24.700
<i>Two weeks into the new school year, I found
the nun's clacker in the school hallway…</i>

37
00:05:24.867 --> 00:05:27.286
<i>… and I was ready for the big leagues.</i>

38
00:05:28.246 --> 00:05:32.625
<i>In church, it was used to alert the girls when
they should stand, sit, kneel and genuflect…</i>

39
00:05:32.792 --> 00:05:35.586
<i>… all based on the number of times
the clacker was pressed.</i>

40
00:05:35.753 --> 00:05:38.589
<i>In my pocket, it was cause for havoc.</i>

41
00:05:47.890 --> 00:05:52.770
You will be defenders of the faith.
You will be soldiers of Christ.

42
00:05:52.937 --> 00:05:54.897
And you will receive the gifts
of the Holy Spirit.

43
00:06:03.197 --> 00:06:07.368
Well, it's going to be a great day
and your parents will be very proud of you.

44
00:06:07.535 --> 00:06:11.038
When you were baptized,
your godparents made promises for you.

45
00:06:11.205 --> 00:06:14.792
- Now you're gonna confirm those promises.
- Let me have the clacker.

46
00:06:14.959 --> 00:06:16.544
- What clacker?
- Now.

47
00:06:17.712 --> 00:06:19.797
Let everyone rise.

48
00:06:23.009 --> 00:06:24.635
Let us pray.

49
00:06:33.603 --> 00:06:36.606
Nuns are such easy targets.

50
00:06:37.523 --> 00:06:39.984
<i>John and I spent more time
in church than the others.</i>

51
00:06:40.151 --> 00:06:43.070
<i>We were the only two to give thought
of entering the priesthood.</i>

52
00:06:43.237 --> 00:06:45.698
<i>We were intrigued by the powers
a priest was given.</i>

53
00:06:45.865 --> 00:06:47.742
<i>A secret world of betrayal and deceit…</i>

54
00:06:47.909 --> 00:06:51.162
<i>… where people openly admitted
dark misdeeds and vile indiscretions.</i>

55
00:06:51.329 --> 00:06:55.166
<i>Confession was better than any book we'd
get our hands on or any movie we'd see…</i>

56
00:06:55.333 --> 00:06:58.502
<i>… because the sins were real,
committed by people we knew.</i>

57
00:06:58.669 --> 00:07:01.339
<i>The temptation to be part of that
was too great to resist.</i>

58
00:07:01.505 --> 00:07:03.466
If we get caught, they'll burn us.

59
00:07:03.841 --> 00:07:05.509
What if our mothers are out there?

60
00:07:05.676 --> 00:07:07.845
What if we end up hearing
their confessions?

61
00:07:08.012 --> 00:07:10.932
- Yeah, what if we hear something worse?
- Like what?

62
00:07:11.349 --> 00:07:15.186
Like a murder.
What if somebody cops to a murder?

63
00:07:15.353 --> 00:07:19.106
Relax. All we gotta do is sit back,
listen and remember not to laugh.

64
00:07:27.031 --> 00:07:29.992
<i>Seconds later, our booth comes to life.</i>

65
00:07:30.159 --> 00:07:33.329
I, uh, sleep with married men.

66
00:07:33.913 --> 00:07:35.957
Men with families.

67
00:07:36.666 --> 00:07:40.878
In the morning, I tell myself
it's the last time, but it never is.

68
00:07:43.422 --> 00:07:44.757
Yes?

69
00:07:45.508 --> 00:07:47.385
You see, I'm, uh…

70
00:07:48.052 --> 00:07:49.220
I'm pregnant.

71
00:07:52.556 --> 00:07:54.392
The father?

72
00:07:54.558 --> 00:07:56.060
Take a number.

73
00:07:56.227 --> 00:07:58.104
What are you going to do?

74
00:07:58.270 --> 00:08:00.064
I know what you want me to do.

75
00:08:00.731 --> 00:08:03.234
And I know what I should do.

76
00:08:03.901 --> 00:08:06.654
I just don't know what I'm gonna do.

77
00:08:08.572 --> 00:08:09.615
Look, I gotta go.

78
00:08:10.741 --> 00:08:13.244
Thanks for listening, fellas.
I really appreciate it.

79
00:08:13.411 --> 00:08:16.872
And I know you'll keep it to yourselves.

80
00:08:22.628 --> 00:08:23.713
She knew.

81
00:08:23.879 --> 00:08:25.506
She knew.

82
00:08:25.673 --> 00:08:28.259
Why do you think she told us all that?

83
00:08:28.968 --> 00:08:32.138
I don't know.
I guess she had to tell somebody.

84
00:08:35.641 --> 00:08:37.768
<i>Father Robert Carrillo
was a longshoreman's son…</i>

85
00:08:37.935 --> 00:08:41.022
<i>… as comfortable sitting on a bar stool
in a back alley saloon…</i>

86
00:08:41.188 --> 00:08:43.607
<i>… as he was standing at the altar
during High Mass.</i>

87
00:08:43.774 --> 00:08:46.652
<i>He toyed with a life of petty crime
before finding his calling.</i>

88
00:08:46.819 --> 00:08:49.363
<i>He was a friend
who just happened to be a priest.</i>

89
00:08:49.530 --> 00:08:51.532
Know what crap like that
does to your body?

90
00:08:51.699 --> 00:08:55.327
Come on, Father, it beats smoking.
And it's cheaper too.

91
00:08:55.494 --> 00:08:56.996
Maybe.

92
00:08:57.455 --> 00:08:59.206
So, what do you hear, anything?

93
00:08:59.373 --> 00:09:00.624
No, nothing.

94
00:09:00.791 --> 00:09:03.169
I hear you're interested
in becoming a priest.

95
00:09:03.335 --> 00:09:04.378
Who says?

96
00:09:04.795 --> 00:09:07.465
Word is you want to get the feel
of a confessional booth.

97
00:09:08.299 --> 00:09:11.260
- I don't know what you're talking about.
- You don't, huh?

98
00:09:11.427 --> 00:09:13.971
- No.
- Well, maybe I got the wrong information.

99
00:09:14.138 --> 00:09:16.557
- Yeah, I guess you did.
- Yeah.

100
00:09:17.224 --> 00:09:18.476
I'll see you later tonight.

101
00:09:19.101 --> 00:09:20.394
What's tonight?

102
00:09:20.936 --> 00:09:24.815
Drop books and magazines off for the elderly
and disabled around the neighborhood.

103
00:09:24.982 --> 00:09:28.527
- Your mother said you'd love to help.
- Yeah, I bet she did.

104
00:09:30.529 --> 00:09:34.200
Shakes, I don't want you
getting into any trouble.

105
00:09:34.742 --> 00:09:36.660
Come on, Father. You know I never do.

106
00:09:36.827 --> 00:09:38.913
That's all I wish for you and your friends.

107
00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:41.707
- That's it?
- That's it. Nothing else, I swear. That's it.

108
00:09:42.166 --> 00:09:43.918
You know, a priest shouldn't swear.

109
00:09:44.085 --> 00:09:46.295
Kids shouldn't listen
to people's confessions.

110
00:09:46.462 --> 00:09:47.505
I'll see you tonight.

111
00:09:47.671 --> 00:09:49.882
- All right, see you.
- Okay.

112
00:09:53.010 --> 00:09:55.638
<i>Michael was the most sexually
experienced of our group…</i>

113
00:09:55.805 --> 00:09:58.474
<i>… which meant he kissed a girl
on more than one occasion.</i>

114
00:09:58.641 --> 00:10:02.269
<i>But his real love was Carol Martinez.
Hell's Kitchen's half-breed…</i>

115
00:10:02.436 --> 00:10:05.439
<i>… half-Puerto Rican, half-Irish,
she was raised by her father…</i>

116
00:10:05.606 --> 00:10:07.483
<i>… her mother having died at childbirth.</i>

117
00:10:07.650 --> 00:10:11.654
<i>Carol stayed pretty much to herself,
but was always comfortable in our company.</i>

118
00:10:11.821 --> 00:10:15.741
<i>We could always count on Carol to stand
sentry on the first night of the Ice Capades.</i>

119
00:10:15.908 --> 00:10:18.536
<i>While crowds of families
lined the front of the Garden…</i>

120
00:10:18.702 --> 00:10:21.789
<i>… waiting to see skaters perform,
we each had one eye in a hole…</i>

121
00:10:21.956 --> 00:10:26.001
<i>… watching two dozen beautiful and nearly
naked women get into their skaters' outfits.</i>

122
00:10:29.004 --> 00:10:30.756
This is what heaven must be about.

123
00:10:36.387 --> 00:10:37.429
Oh, my God.

124
00:10:39.723 --> 00:10:41.725
Hey, Carol, you want to take a look?

125
00:10:41.976 --> 00:10:43.686
Like it's something I haven't seen.

126
00:10:44.436 --> 00:10:46.647
You're so lucky! Ha!

127
00:10:46.897 --> 00:10:51.735
Oh, wow, she's so beautiful,
I could die now and I wouldn't be sad.

128
00:10:51.902 --> 00:10:53.654
<i>When my friends and I were young…</i>

129
00:10:53.821 --> 00:10:56.532
<i>… Hell's Kitchen was run
by a man named King Benny.</i>

130
00:10:56.991 --> 00:11:00.077
When he was young, King
Benny was a hit man for Lucky Luciano.

131
00:11:00.244 --> 00:11:03.455
Lucky Luciano did a lot of good
for this country during World War II.

132
00:11:03.622 --> 00:11:06.417
You ain't gonna read about that
in any fucking history book.

133
00:11:06.584 --> 00:11:09.336
There was talk King Benny
was the shooter of Mad Dog Coll…

134
00:11:09.503 --> 00:11:13.924
… that prick on West 23rd Street.
He ran bootleg with Dutch Schultz.

135
00:11:14.091 --> 00:11:17.219
And he opened up a couple of clubs
with Tough Tony Anastasio.

136
00:11:17.386 --> 00:11:19.597
I was 14 when I first heard about him.

137
00:11:19.763 --> 00:11:22.933
The story goes, as a kid,
he wasn't much of anything.

138
00:11:23.893 --> 00:11:26.437
Always got the shit kicked out of him
in street fights.

139
00:11:26.604 --> 00:11:29.064
And then one day,
and who the fuck knows why…

140
00:11:29.231 --> 00:11:32.276
… some Irish guy about 25 years old…

141
00:11:32.443 --> 00:11:35.988
… he takes King Benny
and he flings him down a flight of stairs.

142
00:11:36.155 --> 00:11:39.074
King Benny
breaks all his teeth in the front.

143
00:11:39.241 --> 00:11:41.285
You know what King Benny does?

144
00:11:41.785 --> 00:11:43.579
He waits.

145
00:11:44.121 --> 00:11:47.416
He waits 8 years
to get even with that prick.

146
00:11:47.583 --> 00:11:51.503
He walks into a public bath house.
The guy's soaking in the tub.

147
00:11:51.670 --> 00:11:56.926
<i>King Benny takes out his front teeth.
He lays them down on the sink.</i>

148
00:11:58.010 --> 00:11:59.929
Then he looks over at the guy
and he says:

149
00:12:01.680 --> 00:12:05.226
<i>"When I look in the mirror,
I see your face."</i>

150
00:12:05.809 --> 00:12:07.853
Then he pulls out a gun…

151
00:12:08.687 --> 00:12:10.564
… and he shoots the guy twice
in each leg.

152
00:12:10.731 --> 00:12:12.691
Bang, bang! Bang, bang!

153
00:12:13.901 --> 00:12:15.152
Then he says to the guy:

154
00:12:15.903 --> 00:12:20.074
<i>"Now when you take a bath,
you see mine."</i>

155
00:12:21.158 --> 00:12:24.036
No one ever fucked with
King Benny after that.

156
00:12:24.703 --> 00:12:26.664
Revenge.

157
00:12:27.581 --> 00:12:29.166
Revenge.

158
00:12:29.333 --> 00:12:31.752
<i>I'm all alone</i>

159
00:12:32.086 --> 00:12:33.921
Can I talk to you for a minute?

160
00:12:34.088 --> 00:12:37.007
I'd like to work for you.
Help you out, whatever you need.

161
00:12:37.716 --> 00:12:41.345
- You're the butcher's kid, am I right?
- Yeah.

162
00:12:41.512 --> 00:12:44.181
Well, what kind of job
are you looking for?

163
00:12:44.348 --> 00:12:45.724
Whatever, it doesn't matter.

164
00:12:46.517 --> 00:12:49.228
Oh, it doesn't matter?

165
00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:52.314
Everybody says
this is the place to come for jobs.

166
00:12:52.856 --> 00:12:54.024
Who is everybody?

167
00:12:54.191 --> 00:12:55.985
People from the neighborhood.

168
00:12:56.151 --> 00:12:57.444
Oh, them.

169
00:12:57.820 --> 00:13:00.364
Let me ask you,
what the fuck do they know?

170
00:13:00.781 --> 00:13:02.116
They know you got jobs.

171
00:13:07.913 --> 00:13:10.124
Sorry I wasted your time.

172
00:13:10.916 --> 00:13:13.794
- Hold on a sec.
- Yeah?

173
00:13:13.961 --> 00:13:15.838
Come back tomorrow if you want to work.

174
00:13:16.005 --> 00:13:17.798
- What time tomorrow?
- Any time.

175
00:13:17.965 --> 00:13:19.049
You'll be here?

176
00:13:19.633 --> 00:13:21.677
I'm always here.

177
00:13:28.350 --> 00:13:30.561
<i>My first job for King Benny
paid $25 a week…</i>

178
00:13:30.728 --> 00:13:33.605
<i>… and ate up only 40 minutes of my time.</i>

179
00:13:33.772 --> 00:13:36.483
<i>In the dark club room,
one guy would hand me a paper bag…</i>

180
00:13:36.650 --> 00:13:39.820
<i>… direct me to one of the two
local police precincts for delivery.</i>

181
00:13:39.987 --> 00:13:41.905
<i>Hey, it was a perfect way
to handle payouts.</i>

182
00:13:42.072 --> 00:13:45.409
Whoa, whoa, whoa!
Come on, let's go! Right here.

183
00:13:45.576 --> 00:13:47.286
See what kind of cash
you got in that bag.

184
00:13:47.453 --> 00:13:49.747
You gotta be nuts.
You know who you're taking off?

185
00:13:49.913 --> 00:13:52.916
Yeah, we know
and we're scared shitless.

186
00:13:53.125 --> 00:13:56.086
Give me the bag.
Give me the fucking bag!

187
00:13:56.253 --> 00:13:58.464
Hey, what you do there?

188
00:13:58.630 --> 00:14:00.799
Answer me! What you do there?

189
00:14:00.966 --> 00:14:03.552
- He took my money.
- You took the money from the boy?

190
00:14:03.719 --> 00:14:06.138
- The money is in the bag.
- Let me have the bag.

191
00:14:06.305 --> 00:14:08.015
- Fuck you!
- Oh, yeah?

192
00:14:08.182 --> 00:14:09.975
- How about now?
- All right, take it easy.

193
00:14:10.142 --> 00:14:14.396
Ah, you're not smart anymore?
This make you stupid?

194
00:14:14.563 --> 00:14:16.023
Let me have the bag.

195
00:14:19.485 --> 00:14:21.195
- Now go.
- What about them?

196
00:14:21.362 --> 00:14:22.404
- You care?
- No.

197
00:14:22.571 --> 00:14:24.198
Then go! Go! Run!

198
00:14:26.367 --> 00:14:27.910
<i>I need somebody with me.</i>

199
00:14:28.077 --> 00:14:29.161
<i>What if the old guy hadn't showed?</i>

200
00:14:29.828 --> 00:14:31.955
- What you need?
- My friends.

201
00:14:32.122 --> 00:14:34.625
Your friends?
What do you think, this is camp?

202
00:14:34.792 --> 00:14:38.045
These kids, you can trust.
I've known them half my life.

203
00:14:39.755 --> 00:14:41.548
Okay, get your friends.

204
00:14:42.299 --> 00:14:44.968
<i>Father Bobby knew my friends
and I worked for King Benny.</i>

205
00:14:45.135 --> 00:14:46.136
<i>He wasn't pleased.</i>

206
00:14:46.303 --> 00:14:48.847
<i>He wasn't worried about the pocket money,
but the next step…</i>

207
00:14:49.014 --> 00:14:52.476
<i>… when they ask you to pick up a gun.
He didn't want that to happen to us.</i>

208
00:14:53.143 --> 00:14:55.729
- Running for King Benny is a good idea?
- It pays.

209
00:14:55.896 --> 00:14:58.649
- It pays? A lot of things pay.
- Not like this.

210
00:14:59.024 --> 00:15:00.359
Whoa!

211
00:15:00.526 --> 00:15:03.070
<i>Most priests liked
to preach from the pulpit.</i>

212
00:15:03.237 --> 00:15:07.157
<i>Father Bobby liked to talk during
the bump and shove of a pickup game.</i>

213
00:15:07.324 --> 00:15:08.575
Good shot!

214
00:15:10.202 --> 00:15:13.205
- I found an art class for you to take.
- I can't afford art class.

215
00:15:13.372 --> 00:15:16.291
You don't have to pay anything.
The teacher's a friend of mine.

216
00:15:16.458 --> 00:15:19.169
I don't know. Could be nothing
but a waste of time, Father.

217
00:15:19.336 --> 00:15:22.172
- Maybe, or it could be the first step.
- First step to what?

218
00:15:22.339 --> 00:15:24.842
- To do something with your life.
- May help you get out.

219
00:15:25.008 --> 00:15:28.470
- You all can get out of here.
- Guys, are we gonna talk or play basketball?

220
00:15:30.681 --> 00:15:31.932
I got a story to tell you.

221
00:15:32.099 --> 00:15:34.810
Ain't the one about lepers, is it?
That gave me nightmares.

222
00:15:34.977 --> 00:15:37.855
No lepers. Michelangelo.
He was born poor, just like you guys.

223
00:15:38.021 --> 00:15:39.940
He was a painter, he was a sculptor.

224
00:15:40.107 --> 00:15:43.402
He takes this job from the pope.
Good money, good work.

225
00:15:44.611 --> 00:15:46.697
Okay, Father,
but why'd the pope call him?

226
00:15:46.864 --> 00:15:50.951
Pope looked for the best guy he could find
to paint the ceiling of his church in Rome.

227
00:15:51.118 --> 00:15:54.496
- Don't sound like that big a job, Father.
- Well, for Michelangelo it was.

228
00:15:54.663 --> 00:15:59.042
Michelangelo needed the job because it paid
more money than he ever had in his life.

229
00:15:59.209 --> 00:16:02.379
He could pay off the loan sharks
that were chasing his father down.

230
00:16:02.546 --> 00:16:06.550
- What's his father?
- He was like a low-level con guy.

231
00:16:06.717 --> 00:16:08.719
Conned people out of money,
goats, sheep—

232
00:16:08.886 --> 00:16:10.304
- Goats?
- Chickens, whatever.

233
00:16:10.471 --> 00:16:12.973
- Chickens?
- You know what happened?

234
00:16:13.140 --> 00:16:16.435
- What?
- He painted a ceiling no one will ever forget.

235
00:16:16.602 --> 00:16:19.062
Painted it like he was touched
by the hand of God.

236
00:16:19.229 --> 00:16:21.899
- Did he pay off the loans?
- Every single one of them.

237
00:16:22.065 --> 00:16:24.985
Hey, how long did it take him,
painting the ceiling and all?

238
00:16:25.152 --> 00:16:27.946
- Took him about nine years.
