the beatings, insults and whatever.

674
00:49:07.946 --> 00:49:10.031
And he learned from it.

675
00:49:10.198 --> 00:49:14.286
Then when the time came for him to
do something, he made his move.

676
00:49:15.078 --> 00:49:18.874
- You admire that?
- No, I respect that.

677
00:49:19.708 --> 00:49:21.585
You got a copy of the book at home?

678
00:49:22.419 --> 00:49:24.212
I got the Classics Illustrated comic.

679
00:49:25.297 --> 00:49:26.923
No, it's not the same thing.

680
00:49:27.090 --> 00:49:29.301
I gotta go.
I'm gonna miss morning roll call.

681
00:49:29.468 --> 00:49:32.929
Wait, wait, wait. One minute, one minute.
I've got something for you.

682
00:49:35.015 --> 00:49:37.559
- Thought you might like to have it.
- Are you serious?

683
00:49:37.726 --> 00:49:40.979
Well, you love the book that
much, you should have a copy of your own.

684
00:49:41.354 --> 00:49:44.566
- I can't pay you.
- No, it's a gift.

685
00:49:44.733 --> 00:49:48.153
- You've gotten gifts before, haven't you?
- It's been a while.

686
00:49:48.445 --> 00:49:50.447
Well, it's my way of saying thanks.

687
00:49:51.072 --> 00:49:52.073
For what?

688
00:49:52.949 --> 00:49:55.494
That somebody listens,
even if it's just one student.

689
00:49:56.536 --> 00:49:57.996
You're a good teacher.

690
00:49:58.163 --> 00:50:02.167
We can discuss the book in class if you
think the count can hold their attention.

691
00:50:02.626 --> 00:50:03.668
He's got a shot.

692
00:50:04.252 --> 00:50:06.421
Any particular section
I should read from?

693
00:50:06.588 --> 00:50:10.133
That's easy.
The part where he escapes from prison.

694
00:50:22.812 --> 00:50:26.149
Here you go, all-star.
Here's your locker room.

695
00:50:33.031 --> 00:50:38.286
<i>It was only a game,
just a touch football game, nothing more.</i>

696
00:50:38.453 --> 00:50:40.914
<i>But a game I wish we had never played.</i>

697
00:50:41.122 --> 00:50:45.669
<i>Guards against inmates.
The guards practiced four times a week.</i>

698
00:50:45.835 --> 00:50:48.630
<i>Our team was picked
the Monday before the game.</i>

699
00:50:48.797 --> 00:50:50.966
<i>We had a two-hour practice.</i>

700
00:50:51.132 --> 00:50:52.384
<i>It didn't matter much.</i>

701
00:50:52.551 --> 00:50:56.346
<i>We weren't supposed to win.
We were just supposed to show up.</i>

702
00:50:56.513 --> 00:50:58.807
Who's the toughest guy out here?

703
00:50:58.974 --> 00:51:02.060
- How do you mean, tough?
- Who can talk and have everyone listen?

704
00:51:02.227 --> 00:51:05.313
Rizzo. Black kid over there.

705
00:51:06.439 --> 00:51:09.943
<i>Michael saw an opening,
a chance to bring the game to our level.</i>

706
00:51:10.110 --> 00:51:14.656
<i>Even out the field.
But he needed help. He needed Rizzo.</i>

707
00:51:14.823 --> 00:51:20.036
<i>Black kid with an Italian name.
With Rizzo on our side, we had a chance.</i>

708
00:51:20.245 --> 00:51:23.665
Look, white boy, I don't know
what you play in the streets. I don't care.

709
00:51:23.832 --> 00:51:25.584
But in here, the guards call the play.

710
00:51:25.750 --> 00:51:27.877
- The play calls for them to win the game.
- Why?

711
00:51:28.044 --> 00:51:29.546
Look, man…

712
00:51:29.713 --> 00:51:33.049
… guards steer clear of me, all right?
Stay back and let me do my time.

713
00:51:33.216 --> 00:51:36.928
I play that game, put a hurt on one of them,
they just might change my cushion.

714
00:51:37.095 --> 00:51:40.557
<i>I'm not saying we gotta
win. I just don't want to take a beating.</i>

715
00:51:40.724 --> 00:51:41.766
<i>You do every day.</i>

716
00:51:42.517 --> 00:51:46.062
- Why is Saturday special?
- Because on Saturday, we can hit back.

717
00:51:47.397 --> 00:51:48.648
Really?

718
00:51:48.815 --> 00:51:52.193
They don't fuck with you like they do us.
They fuck with you another way.

719
00:51:52.360 --> 00:51:54.029
You're just an animal to them.

720
00:51:54.529 --> 00:51:57.115
- I don't give a fuck.
- Yeah, you do.

721
00:51:57.282 --> 00:52:00.410
And beating them on Saturday,
it's not gonna change a thing.

722
00:52:00.869 --> 00:52:02.287
Then why, white boy, why?

723
00:52:02.454 --> 00:52:07.167
To make them feel what we feel,
just for a couple of hours.

724
00:52:08.877 --> 00:52:10.712
Now, don't try anything funny, Sambo.

725
00:52:10.879 --> 00:52:13.298
Nobody will get hurt.
You know what I'm saying?

726
00:52:13.465 --> 00:52:14.507
I call heads.

727
00:52:14.674 --> 00:52:16.760
He calls heads.

728
00:52:17.510 --> 00:52:20.305
He called heads. It is a head.

729
00:52:21.640 --> 00:52:23.308
- Let's go.
- Go.

730
00:52:32.651 --> 00:52:36.321
You're gonna die, motherfucker.
You're gonna fucking die.

731
00:52:46.581 --> 00:52:48.875
None of you motherfuckers can cover me!

732
00:52:49.042 --> 00:52:52.545
We got ourselves a game.
I'm feeling good today.

733
00:52:52.712 --> 00:52:54.547
This shit feels good.

734
00:53:06.601 --> 00:53:08.144
Oh, fuck!

735
00:53:08.311 --> 00:53:09.896
Get the fuck off of me!

736
00:53:17.112 --> 00:53:18.154
Yeah!

737
00:53:22.283 --> 00:53:26.162
- Yeah, keep smiling, you little pissant.
- Yeah.

738
00:53:27.497 --> 00:53:30.625
<i>For 90 minutes,
we took the game out of the prison…</i>

739
00:53:30.792 --> 00:53:32.794
<i>… moved it miles
beyond the locked gates…</i>

740
00:53:32.961 --> 00:53:35.630
<i>… and the sloping hills
of the surrounding countryside…</i>

741
00:53:35.797 --> 00:53:39.467
<i>… and brought it back down to the streets
of the neighborhoods we'd come from.</i>

742
00:53:39.634 --> 00:53:43.138
<i>For those 90 minutes,
we were once again free.</i>

743
00:53:58.737 --> 00:54:01.322
<i>Rizzo! Rizzo! Rizzo!</i>

744
00:54:01.489 --> 00:54:04.117
<i>Rizzo! Rizzo! Rizzo!</i>

745
00:54:04.284 --> 00:54:07.829
<i>Rizzo! Rizzo! Rizzo!</i>

746
00:54:07.996 --> 00:54:11.040
<i>Rizzo! Rizzo! Rizzo!</i>

747
00:54:11.207 --> 00:54:14.502
<i>Rizzo! Rizzo! Rizzo!</i>

748
00:54:14.669 --> 00:54:19.299
Rizzo. Rizzo.

749
00:54:19.549 --> 00:54:22.385
<i>- Rizzo.</i>
- Hey, Nokes.

750
00:54:22.844 --> 00:54:24.512
Good game.

751
00:54:26.389 --> 00:54:32.437
<i>For once, we had a victory,
but it didn't last. It couldn't last.</i>

752
00:54:32.771 --> 00:54:35.523
<i>And all I wanted to do was die.</i>

753
00:54:35.857 --> 00:54:40.361
<i>I was not alone in the hole. I knew my
friends were down in the depths with me.</i>

754
00:54:40.528 --> 00:54:45.074
<i>Each in his own cell, each in his own pain,
suffering his own demons.</i>

755
00:54:45.241 --> 00:54:46.785
<i>Rizzo was there too.</i>

756
00:54:49.454 --> 00:54:52.040
I had lost any sense of time.

757
00:55:31.996 --> 00:55:33.957
I thought you'd never wake up.

758
00:55:34.123 --> 00:55:35.792
I thought I'd never want to.

759
00:55:36.334 --> 00:55:40.213
John and Tommy,
they're on the other side there.

760
00:55:41.047 --> 00:55:42.674
How are they?

761
00:55:43.925 --> 00:55:45.593
They're alive.

762
00:55:46.386 --> 00:55:47.637
Who isn't?

763
00:55:49.597 --> 00:55:51.140
Rizzo.

764
00:55:53.059 --> 00:55:54.435
They killed him?

765
00:55:56.271 --> 00:56:01.568
They took turns beating him until
there was nothing of that kid to beat.

766
00:56:05.280 --> 00:56:07.699
<i>Rizzo was dead because of us.</i>

767
00:56:08.199 --> 00:56:12.078
<i>We made him think that going up against
the guards in a meaningless football game…</i>

768
00:56:12.245 --> 00:56:16.291
<i>… had some value,
that it would give us a reason to go on.</i>

769
00:56:16.541 --> 00:56:19.377
<i>Once again, we were wrong.</i>

770
00:56:20.795 --> 00:56:22.714
<i>They give you your release date yet?</i>

771
00:56:22.881 --> 00:56:24.841
<i>Nokes had a letter from the warden.</i>

772
00:56:25.008 --> 00:56:28.052
Waved it in front of me
and then tore it up.

773
00:56:28.219 --> 00:56:30.054
When do you figure?

774
00:56:30.221 --> 00:56:33.808
I don't know.
End of spring, early summer or something.

775
00:56:34.142 --> 00:56:36.477
I wish we were coming with you.

776
00:56:36.728 --> 00:56:40.106
Would have been nice for all of us
to walk out together, you know?

777
00:56:40.440 --> 00:56:44.402
No use thinking about that.
We're gonna do a full year, not an hour less.

778
00:56:45.987 --> 00:56:49.198
When I get out, I could get Father Bobby
to make a couple phone calls.

779
00:56:49.365 --> 00:56:50.533
Shave a month or two off.

780
00:56:50.700 --> 00:56:54.037
- There's nothing to talk about.
- There's a lot to talk about.

781
00:56:54.203 --> 00:56:57.498
Maybe if people knew what was going on
in here, they'd make a move.

782
00:56:57.665 --> 00:56:59.834
I don't want anybody to know.

783
00:57:00.001 --> 00:57:07.008
Not Father Bobby, King Benny, Fat Mancho,
not my mother. Nobody.

784
00:57:07.842 --> 00:57:12.221
Yeah, I don't either. I mean, I wouldn't know
what to say to anyone who did know.

785
00:57:12.388 --> 00:57:15.350
I can't think of anybody
who needs to hear about it.

786
00:57:15.516 --> 00:57:19.604
I mean, either they won't believe it
or they won't give a shit.

787
00:57:19.771 --> 00:57:23.483
Yeah, I don't even think we should talk
about it once it's over, you know?

788
00:57:24.359 --> 00:57:29.364
We got no choice but to live with it.
And talking makes living it harder.

789
00:57:29.781 --> 00:57:32.450
So we might as well
not even talk about it.

790
00:57:32.700 --> 00:57:34.869
The truth stays with us.

791
00:57:37.622 --> 00:57:40.249
I want to be able to sleep one night…

792
00:57:40.792 --> 00:57:44.295
… and not have to worry who's coming
in my room, what's gonna happen to me.

793
00:57:48.132 --> 00:57:49.926
If I can get that…

794
00:57:51.052 --> 00:57:53.346
… then I'll be happy.

795
00:57:54.889 --> 00:57:58.768
Someday, John, I promise.

796
00:58:14.367 --> 00:58:18.204
<i>I was in my last hours as
an inmate at the Wilkinson Home for Boys.</i>

797
00:58:18.371 --> 00:58:23.793
<i>I was given four copies of my release form,
the final reminder of my time at Wilkinson.</i>

798
00:58:25.378 --> 00:58:30.591
<i>I never heard the key turn in the lock
and I never heard the snap of the bolt.</i>

799
00:58:31.426 --> 00:58:33.594
You should be asleep.

800
00:58:34.137 --> 00:58:36.681
I just wanted to say goodbye.

801
00:58:37.306 --> 00:58:39.100
We all do.

802
00:58:40.977 --> 00:58:42.729
I told him right to his face. I said:

803
00:58:42.895 --> 00:58:46.691
"I don't care if you pay me overtime or not.
I'm not working those kind of hours."

804
00:58:46.858 --> 00:58:48.985
- Did you put in for it?
- Yeah, I put in for it.

805
00:58:49.152 --> 00:58:51.654
Because I put in for it
and they didn't give it to me.

806
00:58:51.821 --> 00:58:55.283
I come in early, three days.
Do they give me overtime? No.

807
00:58:56.284 --> 00:58:59.120
<i>A part of all of us
was left there that night.</i>

808
00:58:59.287 --> 00:59:02.165
<i>A night that will never be removed
from my mind.</i>

809
00:59:02.331 --> 00:59:07.795
<i>The night of June 1, 1968,
the summer of love.</i>

810
00:59:08.463 --> 00:59:11.382
<i>My last night at the
Wilkinson Home for Boys.</i>

811
00:59:57.178 --> 01:00:00.515
<i>At 8:25 p.m.
two men walked through the doors.</i>

812
01:00:00.681 --> 01:00:04.102
<i>The bartender knew their faces.
Most of the neighborhood knew their names.</i>

813
01:00:04.268 --> 01:00:07.021
<i>They were two of the founding members
of the West Side Boys.</i>

814
01:00:07.188 --> 01:00:09.565
<i>They were also its deadliest.</i>

815
01:00:10.316 --> 01:00:13.903
<i>The blond-haired man had been in and out
of jail since he was a teenager.</i>

816
01:00:14.070 --> 01:00:16.823
<i>He robbed and killed at will
or on command.</i>

817
01:00:16.989 --> 01:00:20.076
<i>He's presently a suspect
in four unsolved homicides.</i>

818
01:00:20.243 --> 01:00:24.288
<i>He was an alcoholic and a cocaine abuser
with a fast temper and a faster trigger.</i>

819
01:00:24.455 --> 01:00:28.084
<i>He once shot a mechanic dead
for moving ahead of him in a movie line.</i>

820
01:00:29.418 --> 01:00:31.337
<i>The dark-haired man was
equally deadly…</i>

821
01:00:31.504 --> 01:00:34.549
<i>… and had committed his first murder
at the age of 17.</i>

822
01:00:34.715 --> 01:00:37.093
<i>In return, he was paid $50.</i>

823
01:00:37.260 --> 01:00:38.553
<i>He drank and he did drugs…</i>

824
01:00:38.719 --> 01:00:42.932
<i>… and he had a wife he never saw
living somewhere in Queens.</i>

825
01:00:44.725 --> 01:00:47.937
He's making a noble attempt
to really change things.

826
01:00:48.104 --> 01:00:51.607
- The Republicans will take the House.
- Well, we got a lot of work to do.

827
01:00:51.774 --> 01:00:54.986
- It'll take more than four years—
- They'll take it at the elections.

828
01:00:55.153 --> 01:00:58.114
He's got the charisma. He's gonna do it.

829
01:00:58.281 --> 01:01:00.867
He's our man.
Reagan's the man who's gonna do it.

830
01:01:02.702 --> 01:01:05.163
- Hey, Jerry. What are they talking about?
- Huh?

831
01:01:05.329 --> 01:01:08.374
They're talking about Reagan's speech.

832
01:01:10.293 --> 01:01:13.129
Order those two men some drinks
and put it on my tab.

833
01:01:13.296 --> 01:01:14.630
- And Jerry?
- Yeah.

834
01:01:14.797 --> 01:01:17.758
Tell them that Republicans
are not welcome in Hell's Kitchen…

835
01:01:17.925 --> 01:01:21.721
… and either a political conversion
or a change of conversation is in order.

836
01:01:21.888 --> 01:01:22.930
Sure thing.

837
01:01:28.644 --> 01:01:29.687
Yeah?

838
01:01:29.854 --> 01:01:32.940
The gentlemen there would like
to buy you a drink on one condition.

839
01:01:33.107 --> 01:01:37.195
You know the rules:
no religion, no politics.

840
01:01:37.361 --> 01:01:39.363
You get my meaning?

841
01:01:46.204 --> 01:01:48.414
<i>Henderson with the miss,
Bird underneath…</i>

842
01:01:48.581 --> 01:01:50.583
<i>… he gets the garbage and scores.</i>

843
01:01:56.172 --> 01:01:58.716
Order something for me.
I gotta go to the bathroom.

844
01:02:29.455 --> 01:02:31.624
Can I help you with something, chief?

845
01:02:32.500 --> 01:02:34.210
Not right now.

846
01:02:35.586 --> 01:02:37.421
Enjoy the rest of your meal.

847
01:03:22.758 --> 01:03:26.721
I, uh, I ordered the brisket
on a roll with fries…

848
01:03:26.887 --> 01:03:29.640
… and, uh, two baskets of soda bread.

849
01:03:29.807 --> 01:03:32.226
I know how you like that shit.

850
01:03:32.393 --> 01:03:34.228
Is that okay by you?

851
01:03:35.688 --> 01:03:39.775
Take a look at the guy at the table.
Take a good look.

852
01:03:50.661 --> 01:03:52.705
Motherfucker.

853
01:04:18.314 --> 01:04:19.982
That's him.

854
01:04:20.232 --> 01:04:22.485
Are you fucking kidding me?

855
01:04:25.279 --> 01:04:26.322
Bingo.

856
01:04:51.639 --> 01:04:53.307
This is amazing.

857
01:04:53.474 --> 01:04:55.768
Hello. It's been a long time.

858
01:04:57.269 --> 01:04:59.313
Who the fuck are you guys?

859
01:05:00.731 --> 01:05:02.149
Hey.

860
01:05:02.650 --> 01:05:04.402
Who the fuck asked you to sit down?

861
01:05:04.568 --> 01:05:08.447
I thought you'd be happy to see us.
I guess I was wrong.

862
01:05:09.782 --> 01:05:12.159
You know,
I thought you'd do a lot better, you know?

863
01:05:12.660 --> 01:05:15.496
You know, with all that training,
all that time you put in…

864
01:05:15.663 --> 01:05:18.999
… just to end up watching someone else's
money. That seems like a waste.

865
01:05:19.166 --> 01:05:21.335
I'm asking for the last time,
what do you want?

866
01:05:21.502 --> 01:05:24.463
Why don't you take your time?
It'll come to you.

867
01:05:29.135 --> 01:05:31.512
- I could see how he might forget us.
- Yeah.

868
01:05:31.679 --> 01:05:34.473
We were just something for you
and your friends to play with.

869
01:05:34.640 --> 01:05:40.729
It's a little harder for us to forget.
You gave us so much more to remember.

870
01:05:42.731 --> 01:05:44.483
Can't quite place us, can you, chief?

871
01:05:44.900 --> 01:05:46.735
Let me help you out.

872
01:05:46.902 --> 01:05:50.114
You're looking at
John Reilly and Tommy Marcano.

873
01:05:56.078 --> 01:05:57.705
Oh, yeah.

874
01:06:00.374 --> 01:06:02.251
Yeah, that's right.

875
01:06:08.382 --> 01:06:10.426
That was a long time ago.

876
01:06:13.012 --> 01:06:14.263
So how you been?

877
01:06:14.805 --> 01:06:16.682
Yeah, we ain't kids now.

878
01:06:17.099 --> 01:06:18.976
Ah, so, what do you want?

879
01:06:19.977 --> 01:06:23.147
What I've always wanted
is to watch you die.

880
01:06:27.443 --> 01:06:28.903
Oh.

881
01:06:29.069 --> 01:06:31.322
You ordered the meat loaf.

882
01:06:31.822 --> 01:06:35.117
The brisket's really good here,
only you'll never know it.

883
01:06:36.076 --> 01:06:37.578
You fucked up.

884
01:06:51.050 --> 01:06:53.344
You were scared little pricks…

885
01:06:54.178 --> 01:06:55.846
… both of you.

886
01:06:56.514 --> 01:06:58.140
All of you, ha, ha…

887
01:06:59.266 --> 01:07:02.102
… scared shitless. But I—

888
01:07:03.145 --> 01:07:06.565
I tried to make you tough.
I tried to make you hard.

889
01:07:06.732 --> 01:07:08.317
I had you all wrong, then, Nokes.

890
01:07:08.484 --> 01:07:12.029
All this time, I thought you just liked
fucking and beating up little boys.

891
01:07:12.196 --> 01:07:15.991
You two motherfuckers are gonna burn
in hell. You're gonna burn in hell.

892
01:07:16.158 --> 01:07:18.327
Yeah, after you.

893
01:07:23.123 --> 01:07:25.334
Did that hurt, Nokes?

894
01:08:01.912 --> 01:08:03.455
Jerry.

895
01:08:03.831 --> 01:08:07.334
Sorry, should have made
those brisket sandwiches to go.

896
01:08:12.131 --> 01:08:14.216
- Jesus!
- Aah!

897
01:08:18.762 --> 01:08:20.264
<i>John Reilly, how do you plead?</i>

898
01:08:20.431 --> 01:08:22.308
<i>Not guilty, Your Honor.</i>

899
01:08:22.474 --> 01:08:24.393
<i>Thomas Marcano?</i>

900
01:08:24.935 --> 01:08:26.520
<i>Not guilty, Your Honor.</i>

901
01:08:26.687 --> 01:08:30.941
<i>John Reilly and Thomas Marcano,
you are hereby held without bail.</i>

902
01:08:31.567 --> 01:08:35.154
<i>In all the years since Wilkinson's,
we had never once spoken to each other…</i>

903
01:08:35.321 --> 01:08:36.947
<i>… about what had happened there.</i>

904
01:08:37.114 --> 01:08:41.910
<i>We remained caring friends,
but the relationship had been altered.</i>

905
01:08:42.077 --> 01:08:46.206
<i>We drifted together, always wondering
if that moment would arrive…</i>

906
01:08:46.373 --> 01:08:48.542
<i>… that would force us
to deal with the past.</i>

907
01:09:01.930 --> 01:09:03.932
One down, Shakes.

908
01:09:04.600 --> 01:09:05.643
One down.

909
01:09:07.186 --> 01:09:08.854
One what?

910
01:09:10.147 --> 01:09:14.068
One Sean Nokes.

911
01:09:14.735 --> 01:09:16.278
Nokes?

912
01:09:23.786 --> 01:09:25.412
<i>At the time of Nokes' shooting…</i>

913
01:09:25.579 --> 01:09:28.666
<i>… Michael was working as an
Assistant New York District Attorney.</i>

914
01:09:28.832 --> 01:09:32.336
<i>I got a call that he wanted to meet me
on 45th Street in Queens.</i>

915
01:09:32.503 --> 01:09:34.338
<i>Then he hung up.</i>

916
01:09:36.423 --> 01:09:38.759
Hey. So, what did they say?

917
01:09:38.926 --> 01:09:40.844
- What?
- John and Tommy. What did they say?

918
01:09:41.011 --> 01:09:43.681
- It's a little cloak and dagger, isn't it, Mike?
- Come on.

919
01:09:43.847 --> 01:09:46.558
Nokes. Did they talk about him?

920
01:09:47.518 --> 01:09:49.603
- John did.
- Yeah?

921
01:09:49.937 --> 01:09:51.397
What did he say?

922
01:09:51.563 --> 01:09:55.150
He said, "One down, Shakes. One down."

923
01:09:57.778 --> 01:10:00.489
- They hired Danny Snyder as the lawyer?
- It's temporary.

924
01:10:00.656 --> 01:10:04.034
- King Benny will move in one of his lawyers.
- No, don't let him do that.

925
01:10:04.201 --> 01:10:06.662
- Snyder's perfect.
- The guy's a fall-down drunk.

926
01:10:06.829 --> 01:10:10.499
- I'm telling you, he's perfect.
- Perfect for what?

927
01:10:13.961 --> 01:10:15.921
- You covering this for your newspaper?
- Me?

928
01:10:16.088 --> 01:10:18.632
- Yeah.
- I'm a timetable clerk, Mikey.

929
01:10:18.799 --> 01:10:22.928
Ask me what movie's playing at what time.
I'm lucky they let me in the building.

930
01:10:26.807 --> 01:10:27.933
Get some coffee?

931
01:10:28.726 --> 01:10:30.477
Let's take a walk.

932
01:10:40.320 --> 01:10:43.449
I'm gonna prosecute John
and Tommy in an open court.

933
01:10:43.991 --> 01:10:47.327
- What, are you fucking nuts?
- Hey, just hear me out.

934
01:10:47.494 --> 01:10:50.247
You should stay home tomorrow.
Call in sick, save your life.

935
01:10:50.414 --> 01:10:52.916
I'm not taking this case to win.

936
01:10:53.500 --> 01:10:56.128
I'm taking this case to lose.

937
01:10:56.503 --> 01:10:59.006
- What does that mean?
- Ha, ha.

938
01:11:00.007 --> 01:11:02.301
It means it's payback time.

939
01:11:02.468 --> 01:11:07.514
Look, John and Tommy started this.
It's begun.

940
01:11:07.681 --> 01:11:12.019
It's messy, it's not how I had it planned,
but here it is.

941
01:11:12.561 --> 01:11:15.564
And you and I, we can finish it.

942
01:11:16.023 --> 01:11:17.524
Finish what, Mike?

943
01:11:19.860 --> 01:11:21.779
You read
<i>The Count of Monte Cristo</i> lately?

944
01:11:23.280 --> 01:11:25.866
I don't know. Ten years ago.

945
01:11:26.700 --> 01:11:29.912
You see, I read a little bit
of it every night.

946
01:11:30.162 --> 01:11:35.292
I read words like "revenge."
Sweet lasting revenge.

947
01:11:36.502 --> 01:11:38.504
Payback time.

948
01:11:39.755 --> 01:11:41.632
It's our time.

949
01:11:42.174 --> 01:11:43.425
What are you saying, Mike?

950
01:11:44.384 --> 01:11:47.387
I'm saying it's time
for all of us to get a taste.

951
01:11:48.806 --> 01:11:51.058
I'm saying it's time
to put an end to this.

952
01:11:53.143 --> 01:11:54.561
Let's walk.

953
01:11:57.731 --> 01:12:01.568
I asked for the case. I told them I was from
the same neighborhood as the accused…

954
01:12:01.735 --> 01:12:03.612
… knew the mentality of the area.
Blah, blah.

955
01:12:03.779 --> 01:12:05.280
They bought it.

956
01:12:05.447 --> 01:12:07.741
And the connection between John,
Tommy and Nokes?

957
01:12:07.908 --> 01:12:11.745
What connection? All juvenile records
are destroyed after seven years.

958
01:12:11.912 --> 01:12:13.831
We were never at Wilkinson's.

959
01:12:16.959 --> 01:12:20.671
We gotta go after the guards.
I gotta get Wilkinson's.

960
01:12:21.046 --> 01:12:22.422
Bring it all down.

961
01:12:22.589 --> 01:12:25.926
Adam Styler, plain-clothes cop,
works Narcotics in Queens.

962
01:12:26.093 --> 01:12:29.763
Known to shake down dealers for dope
and cash. He's got a cocaine problem.

963
01:12:29.930 --> 01:12:31.598
Other personal information there.

964
01:12:31.765 --> 01:12:35.102
Henry Addison, now works for the mayor,
if you can fucking believe that.

965
01:12:35.269 --> 01:12:37.604
He's a Community Outreach Director
in Brooklyn.

966
01:12:37.771 --> 01:12:41.608
His sexual habits haven't changed.
He still likes sex with young boys.

967
01:12:41.775 --> 01:12:45.279
Ralph Ferguson, works in a
Social Service agency in Long Island.

968
01:12:45.445 --> 01:12:48.490
- How long you been working on this?
- Recently divorced, one child.

969
01:12:48.657 --> 01:12:51.034
And on weekends,
teaches Catholic Sunday school.

970
01:12:51.201 --> 01:12:55.581
- Well, it seems clean, then, right?
- That's exactly why I want the piece of shit.

971
01:12:55.747 --> 01:12:58.083
Plan is to call Ferguson in
as a character witness.

972
01:12:58.250 --> 01:13:00.794
Get him talking about his best friend,
Sean Nokes.

973
01:13:00.961 --> 01:13:04.882
Once I got him on the stand,
I'm gonna open the door to Wilkinson's.

974
01:13:05.549 --> 01:13:07.009
Mike…

975
01:13:08.427 --> 01:13:10.679
… are you sure you want to go this way?

976
01:13:13.265 --> 01:13:16.101
I mean, we buried this a long time ago.

977
01:13:17.853 --> 01:13:20.314
Do you still sleep with the light on?

978
01:13:25.027 --> 01:13:28.071
John and Tommy, do you want them
to know anything about this?

979
01:13:28.238 --> 01:13:31.158
No, it'll play better in court
if they don't know.

980
01:13:42.961 --> 01:13:46.423
<i>The not-guilty verdict had to be
a verdict that no one would dare question.</i>

981
01:13:46.924 --> 01:13:49.551
<i>Danny Snyder was to remain
as Tommy and John's attorney.</i>

982
01:13:51.053 --> 01:13:53.347
<i>Michael's plan relied heavily
on Hell's Kitchen…</i>

983
01:13:53.513 --> 01:13:55.390
<i>… to deliver information and keep quiet.</i>

984
01:13:55.557 --> 01:13:58.143
<i>Both were skills the neighborhood
had in abundance.</i>

985
01:13:58.310 --> 01:14:00.520
<i>We'd set up a simple method
of communication.</i>

986
01:14:00.687 --> 01:14:03.148
<i>If Michael was sending,
messages were left at work…</i>

987
01:14:03.315 --> 01:14:05.734
<i>… for me to call
my nonexistent girlfriend, Gloria.</i>

988
01:14:06.276 --> 01:14:09.279
<i>To get word to Michael,
I'd have someone from the neighborhood…</i>

989
01:14:09.446 --> 01:14:11.698
<i>… pick up an edition of</i>
The New York Times…

990
01:14:11.865 --> 01:14:14.993
<i>… write the word "Edmund"
in the corner of the Metro section…</i>

991
01:14:15.160 --> 01:14:17.871
<i>… and drop it in front
of Michael's apartment.</i>

992
01:14:22.209 --> 01:14:26.546
<i>For this to succeed, we needed total secrecy
of the only people we completely trusted.</i>

993
01:14:26.713 --> 01:14:28.674
<i>The plan depended on keeping
Michael alive.</i>

994
01:14:28.840 --> 01:14:33.095
<i>Meant word had to get to John and Tommy's
killing crew that he was not an open target.</i>

995
01:14:33.261 --> 01:14:36.640
<i>After this night,
Michael would not be available to any of us.</i>

996
01:14:36.807 --> 01:14:39.559
<i>The only time we would see him
would be in court.</i>

997
01:14:39.726 --> 01:14:41.937
- That's it?
- Not quite.

998
01:14:42.104 --> 01:14:44.815
Four witnesses who saw the shooting
are willing to testify.

999
01:14:44.982 --> 01:14:46.400
Gotta get that number down.

1000
01:14:46.566 --> 01:14:49.736
- I'll talk to King Benny.
- Good.

1001
01:14:49.903 --> 01:14:53.532
I can handle two,
but, uh, you gotta get us one for our side.

1002
01:14:53.907 --> 01:14:56.326
- One of what?
- One witness.

1003
01:14:56.493 --> 01:15:00.205
A witness who'll put John and Tommy
somewhere else on the night of the murder.

1004
01:15:00.372 --> 01:15:01.957
A witness they can't touch.

1005
01:15:03.583 --> 01:15:05.335
Don't they got a name for that?

1006
01:15:05.502 --> 01:15:08.672
- A judge would call it perjury.
- Oh, nice.

1007
01:15:08.839 --> 01:15:12.300
- And what are we calling it?
- A favor.

1008
01:15:15.220 --> 01:15:16.805
Get up. Come on.

1009
01:15:19.558 --> 01:15:21.351
- Tony.
- Yeah, King?

1010
01:15:21.518 --> 01:15:23.687
Bring Danny Snyder to see me.

1011
01:15:23.854 --> 01:15:25.272
Who, Danny Snyder, the lawyer?

1012
01:15:25.439 --> 01:15:28.275
- You know more than one Danny Snyder?
- No, King.

1013
01:15:28.442 --> 01:15:30.610
Bring me the one you know.

1014
01:15:48.920 --> 01:15:53.341
I can't do this now. You gotta
know that. It's been a long time for me.

1015
01:15:55.635 --> 01:15:59.181
I mean, you need somebody younger.
You know, somebody like I used to be.

1016
01:15:59.347 --> 01:16:01.141
Younger is not better.

1017
01:16:01.308 --> 01:16:04.853
Doesn't have experience,
doesn't know its way around a courthouse.

1018
01:16:05.020 --> 01:16:07.064
Hey, I'm lucky I can find the courthouse.

1019
01:16:08.565 --> 01:16:12.903
I had only four cases last year.
You know how many I won?

1020
01:16:13.070 --> 01:16:16.698
None. That's how many, none.

1021
01:16:17.115 --> 01:16:22.120
In two of them,
I, uh, think the jury blamed me personally.

1022
01:16:22.287 --> 01:16:24.706
They must've been innocent.

1023
01:16:25.082 --> 01:16:28.168
It's tough to get innocent men off a rap.

1024
01:16:28.335 --> 01:16:30.587
Wasn't even planning on going
to court with this.

1025
01:16:30.754 --> 01:16:33.590
I was just gonna plea it down
best I could and walk away.

1026
01:16:33.757 --> 01:16:36.760
I wasn't planning on taking
this to trial, sir.

1027
01:16:36.927 --> 01:16:39.304
Well, your plans have been changed.

1028
01:16:39.471 --> 01:16:44.434
Well, I am afraid that I'll make a mistake
and say the wrong thing…

1029
01:16:45.685 --> 01:16:48.939
… make a wrong turn somewhere,
and you don't want to take that risk.

1030
01:16:49.106 --> 01:16:51.316
- Life is risk.
- I'm sorry.

1031
01:16:52.025 --> 01:16:53.318
Life is risk.

1032
01:16:53.735 --> 01:16:55.403
Life is a risk?

1033
01:16:55.570 --> 01:16:57.656
- Mm-hm.
- Uh-huh.

1034
01:16:59.533 --> 01:17:01.409
I haven't been in here before.

1035
01:17:03.161 --> 01:17:04.538
What do you need me to do?

1036
01:17:04.704 --> 01:17:10.085
Listen, you're gonna be given the answers
and the questions.

1037
01:17:10.252 --> 01:17:14.589
All you have to do is read.
You can read, can't you?

1038
01:17:14.756 --> 01:17:16.049
Is it in English?

1039
01:17:16.216 --> 01:17:20.011
Just don't drift,
don't drink and don't lose.

1040
01:17:20.887 --> 01:17:22.222
What if I do lose?

1041
01:17:22.389 --> 01:17:25.016
Then you go down for the dirt nap.

1042
01:17:25.851 --> 01:17:28.436
Never heard that expression before.

1043
01:17:29.771 --> 01:17:30.856
Dirt nap.

1044
01:17:32.691 --> 01:17:34.776
I'm not really cut out for this anymore.

1045
01:17:34.943 --> 01:17:39.906
I mean, a guy gets hit by a bus,
you know, and sues, I like that.

1046
01:17:40.073 --> 01:17:44.411
Some lady, uh, slips in a supermarket,
I'm with her. A guy—

1047
01:17:44.578 --> 01:17:45.954
The discussion is over.

1048
01:17:46.121 --> 01:17:50.000
I'm an alcoholic. This is a murder case.
This isn't for me.

1049
01:17:50.167 --> 01:17:52.210
- It was once.
- Yes, but—

1050
01:17:52.377 --> 01:17:54.921
Before you let the drink lead.

1051
01:17:55.714 --> 01:17:59.676
Be sober by tomorrow.
And don't look so worried, Snyder.

1052
01:17:59.843 --> 01:18:03.430
You got nothing to lose,
just like the rest of us.

1053
01:18:03.597 --> 01:18:05.348
I don't want to be a burden to you…

1054
01:18:05.515 --> 01:18:09.060
… but, you know, aside or along with
my alcohol problem…

1055
01:18:09.227 --> 01:18:12.731
… I have a slight drug problem.
I mean, nothing big, just—

1056
01:18:13.481 --> 01:18:14.733
Go away.

1057
01:18:25.202 --> 01:18:27.162
<i>Within days of Michael taking the case…</i>

1058
01:18:27.329 --> 01:18:29.789
<i>… the West Side Boys got a visit
from King Benny.</i>

1059
01:18:29.956 --> 01:18:33.543
<i>The King requested that the verbal abuse
directed towards Michael continue.</i>

1060
01:18:33.710 --> 01:18:36.963
<i>Cries of "traitor" and "gutter-rat"
were heard up and down the avenue.</i>

1061
01:18:37.130 --> 01:18:39.549
<i>But there was never to be
a death move against him.</i>

1062
01:18:39.716 --> 01:18:43.970
<i>The hit on Michael Sullivan, if there was to
be one, could only come from King Benny.</i>

1063
01:18:44.137 --> 01:18:46.640
<i>The underground word,
the only one that mattered…</i>

1064
01:18:46.806 --> 01:18:50.143
<i>… had spread through the streets
with the speed of a late-night bullet.</i>

1065
01:18:53.980 --> 01:18:56.942
<i>King Benny's sleepers
were making their play.</i>

1066
01:18:57.108 --> 01:19:00.737
<i>"Sleepers" was a street name for anyone
who spent time in a juvenile facility.</i>

1067
01:19:10.580 --> 01:19:13.458
Hey! You gonna pay for that,
you little prick?

1068
01:19:13.625 --> 01:19:17.671
I need your help, fat man.
Need a big favor. I'll be outside.

1069
01:19:18.338 --> 01:19:19.756
King Benny been to see you?

1070
01:19:19.923 --> 01:19:23.510
Oh, my goodness.
What a fucking thing we put together, huh?

1071
01:19:23.677 --> 01:19:28.223
You have a drunk lawyer on one side,
a kid lawyer on the other.

1072
01:19:28.390 --> 01:19:31.685
Fucking paperboy
making like Dick Tracy.

1073
01:19:31.851 --> 01:19:35.730
There are four sets of eyeballs
that saw the whole thing.

1074
01:19:35.897 --> 01:19:38.942
Meanwhile, the two on trial
kill more people than cancer.

1075
01:19:39.109 --> 01:19:41.444
Fucking General Custer
has a better shot at a walk.

1076
01:19:41.611 --> 01:19:43.363
No connection with the guard and us.

1077
01:19:43.530 --> 01:19:45.365
The cops think
it's a drug-related homicide.

1078
01:19:45.532 --> 01:19:47.409
We just need you to pull a few strings.

1079
01:19:47.575 --> 01:19:51.121
You know, if you get caught on this,
you're looking straight at serious.

1080
01:19:51.288 --> 01:19:54.040
I'm talking real jail. The big house.

1081
01:20:00.547 --> 01:20:02.424
They are not good boys anymore.

1082
01:20:03.300 --> 01:20:06.845
They're killers now, cold as stone.

1083
01:20:08.221 --> 01:20:12.350
I know. I know what they were and I know
what they are and it's not about that.

1084
01:20:13.018 --> 01:20:17.689
It's not worth it,
throwing away life just to get even.

1085
01:20:18.106 --> 01:20:20.108
You and the lawyer have a chance
to get out.

1086
01:20:20.275 --> 01:20:21.609
To get out the right way.

1087
01:20:21.776 --> 01:20:24.404
There's no choice. Not for us.

1088
01:20:28.408 --> 01:20:30.577
<i>On occasion, I'd have dinner with Carol.</i>

1089
01:20:30.744 --> 01:20:34.664
<i>She still lived in the neighborhood
and was a social worker in the South Bronx.</i>

1090
01:20:34.831 --> 01:20:38.084
<i>Her concern for us was undiminished
by the passing years.</i>

1091
01:20:38.251 --> 01:20:41.796
<i>Whenever we went out as a group, Carol
would walk between Michael and John…</i>

1092
01:20:41.963 --> 01:20:44.174
<i>… grasping their arms…</i>

1093
01:20:44.341 --> 01:20:46.426
<i>… in step between
the lawyer and the killer.</i>

1094
01:20:46.593 --> 01:20:50.638
Mug me or marry me, Shakes.
I'm too tired for anything else.

1095
01:20:51.264 --> 01:20:53.266
Would you settle for a couple beers,
Carol?

1096
01:20:55.310 --> 01:20:57.145
If that's your best offer.

1097
01:20:58.563 --> 01:21:00.273
I'll throw in a hug and a kiss.

1098
01:21:01.191 --> 01:21:02.984
Deal.

1099
01:21:06.821 --> 01:21:07.989
<i>Oh, what a night</i>

1100
01:21:08.156 --> 01:21:11.409
- You look tired.
- Thank you.

1101
01:21:11.576 --> 01:21:13.870
They don't give you time to sleep
in this new job of yours?

1102
01:21:14.037 --> 01:21:17.791
<i>What a very special time for me</i>

1103
01:21:18.500 --> 01:21:20.460
So how much do you know?

1104
01:21:20.960 --> 01:21:23.296
Just what the neighborhood says.

1105
01:21:23.546 --> 01:21:26.132
And what I read in papers like yours.

1106
01:21:26.299 --> 01:21:27.884
What does the neighborhood say?

1107
01:21:28.051 --> 01:21:29.928
They're gonna put Johnny
and Tommy away.

1108
01:21:30.095 --> 01:21:32.180
Their best friend's
gonna be the one to do it.

1109
01:21:32.347 --> 01:21:35.225
- You believe that?
- It's hard not to, Shakes.

1110
01:21:35.392 --> 01:21:39.938
Oh, unless we all have it wrong.
He did take the fucking case.

1111
01:21:40.105 --> 01:21:43.149
- He did take the case.
- What else is there to say?

1112
01:21:45.151 --> 01:21:49.155
You know Michael very well,
maybe even better than I do.

1113
01:21:49.322 --> 01:21:51.991
Yeah, I thought I did. Now I don't know.

1114
01:21:52.158 --> 01:21:54.327
- You do know.
- I don't know!

1115
01:21:54.494 --> 01:21:55.995
He went and asked for the case.

1116
01:21:56.162 --> 01:21:58.998
Now, you tell me,
what the hell kind of friend is that?

1117
01:21:59.165 --> 01:22:01.334
The best kind.

1118
01:22:01.626 --> 01:22:04.170
The kind who'll throw away everything
to help his friends.

1119
01:22:04.337 --> 01:22:07.924
<i>Hypnotizing, mesmerizing me</i>

1120
01:22:08.091 --> 01:22:10.343
What are you telling me, Shakes?

1121
01:22:10.969 --> 01:22:15.014
You know this neighborhood, Carol.
Everything's a shakedown or a scam.

1122
01:22:15.181 --> 01:22:17.559
Why should this be any different?

1123
01:22:22.981 --> 01:22:24.732
