02:11:38.475 --> 02:11:41.478
And there isn't anything you wouldn't do
for them, am I right?

1809
02:11:41.645 --> 02:11:44.398
Anything in my power to do,
I would make it a point.

1810
02:11:45.190 --> 02:11:48.610
Like a father, a good father,
looking out for one of his sons.

1811
02:11:49.444 --> 02:11:52.572
- Something along those lines, yes.
- Is it true, as a good father…

1812
02:11:52.739 --> 02:11:55.992
… you'd want to protect them
from something they shouldn't have done?

1813
02:11:56.159 --> 02:11:58.078
As much as I would want
to protect them…

1814
02:11:58.245 --> 02:12:00.497
… from something
someone else said they did, yes.

1815
02:12:01.081 --> 02:12:02.124
Like a murder?

1816
02:12:02.833 --> 02:12:04.167
Yes, like a murder.

1817
02:12:05.460 --> 02:12:07.462
Let me get this straight, then.

1818
02:12:07.629 --> 02:12:09.965
No one knew you went to the game
or saw you there.

1819
02:12:10.132 --> 02:12:13.343
No one saw you buy tickets.
There's no record you even bought tickets.

1820
02:12:13.510 --> 02:12:16.930
You have no receipt for the tickets.
Am I correct?

1821
02:12:18.557 --> 02:12:19.766
Yes, that's correct.

1822
02:12:19.933 --> 02:12:22.018
Then how do we really know, Father?

1823
02:12:22.185 --> 02:12:26.398
How do we know you and the two defendants
were at the game on the night of the murder?

1824
02:12:27.774 --> 02:12:31.445
I'm telling you as a witness
and as a priest, we were at the game.

1825
02:12:31.611 --> 02:12:35.532
Yes, as a priest, and a priest wouldn't lie.
Am I right?

1826
02:12:36.032 --> 02:12:39.035
A priest with ticket stubs
wouldn't need to lie.

1827
02:12:39.202 --> 02:12:43.832
And I always keep the stubs.

1828
02:12:47.836 --> 02:12:49.004
Do you want to see?

1829
02:12:56.052 --> 02:12:58.221
Why is that, Father?
Uh, why do you keep the stubs?

1830
02:12:59.139 --> 02:13:02.893
Because you never know when someone
might want more than your word.

1831
02:13:04.144 --> 02:13:06.229
Has anyone questioned your word
before today?

1832
02:13:06.396 --> 02:13:08.815
No, no one ever has.

1833
02:13:09.232 --> 02:13:11.735
But there's a first time for everything.

1834
02:13:20.911 --> 02:13:24.039
I have no further questions.
Thank you, Father.

1835
02:13:25.916 --> 02:13:28.210
Thank you, Father. You may step down.

1836
02:13:35.592 --> 02:13:39.262
<i>I've never recovered from seeing
Father Bobby take the stand and lie for us…</i>

1837
02:13:39.429 --> 02:13:42.474
<i>… to even the score for John and Tommy.</i>

1838
02:13:42.641 --> 02:13:46.144
<i>He didn't just testify for them,
he testified against Wilkinson…</i>

1839
02:13:46.311 --> 02:13:48.939
<i>… and the evil that had lived there
for too long.</i>

1840
02:13:49.105 --> 02:13:51.650
<i>Still, I was sorry he had to do it.</i>

1841
02:13:58.490 --> 02:14:01.284
With respect to the charge of murder
in the second degree…

1842
02:14:01.451 --> 02:14:05.330
… do you find the defendant, John Reilly,
guilty or not guilty?

1843
02:14:05.497 --> 02:14:07.457
- Not guilty.
- With respect to the charge…

1844
02:14:07.624 --> 02:14:09.167
… murder in the second degree…

1845
02:14:09.334 --> 02:14:14.130
… do you find the defendant,
Thomas Marcano, guilty or not guilty?

1846
02:14:14.297 --> 02:14:15.674
Not guilty.

1847
02:14:16.299 --> 02:14:20.512
<i>Thank you very much.
This jury is discharged.</i>

1848
02:14:40.323 --> 02:14:43.910
- Hi, how are you? Could I get a hot dog?
- Yeah, sure.

1849
02:14:44.077 --> 02:14:46.621
- Uh, mustard, relish.
- No problem.

1850
02:14:46.788 --> 02:14:48.540
A lot of relish.

1851
02:14:51.001 --> 02:14:53.503
- Give him two napkins.
- Yeah.

1852
02:14:58.091 --> 02:15:00.343
You did good in there, counselor.

1853
02:15:02.012 --> 02:15:03.847
So, what happens to you now?

1854
02:15:04.014 --> 02:15:06.349
What happens? I walk away.

1855
02:15:07.517 --> 02:15:10.353
I'll wait a few weeks,
I'll hand in my notice.

1856
02:15:10.520 --> 02:15:13.064
And after the way I handled this case…

1857
02:15:13.231 --> 02:15:16.192
… they won't be in a rush
to keep me from the door.

1858
02:15:18.111 --> 02:15:20.905
So you switch to the other side,
work as a defense lawyer.

1859
02:15:21.072 --> 02:15:22.782
The money's better.

1860
02:15:22.949 --> 02:15:26.661
There's always gonna be more bad guys
than good, Mikey.

1861
02:15:27.704 --> 02:15:31.291
And can you imagine the work you'd get
from John and Tommy's crew?

1862
02:15:31.458 --> 02:15:33.251
That's a house and a pool.

1863
02:15:35.253 --> 02:15:36.963
Not for me.

1864
02:15:37.672 --> 02:15:40.216
I've seen all the law I want to see.

1865
02:15:40.884 --> 02:15:43.928
- It's time for something else.
- Like what?

1866
02:15:44.095 --> 02:15:45.388
Let you know when I know.

1867
02:15:46.640 --> 02:15:48.808
You're too old
to play for the Yankees…

1868
02:15:48.975 --> 02:15:50.602
… and you're too young to take up golf.

1869
02:15:50.769 --> 02:15:55.148
Why are you shooting holes through
all my plans? You're gonna make me panic.

1870
02:15:55.732 --> 02:15:58.193
You'll work it out. You always have.

1871
02:16:03.365 --> 02:16:05.784
It's time for quiet, Shakes.

1872
02:16:07.369 --> 02:16:11.247
I just want to shut my eyes
and not have to see the places I've been.

1873
02:16:13.333 --> 02:16:15.126
I'm weary.

1874
02:16:18.546 --> 02:16:20.340
I don't know.

1875
02:16:22.926 --> 02:16:25.679
Maybe I'll get lucky,
forget I was even there.

1876
02:16:26.638 --> 02:16:28.890
Well, don't disappear on me, counselor.

1877
02:16:30.350 --> 02:16:32.060
I may need a good lawyer one day.

1878
02:16:32.227 --> 02:16:35.563
- Hey, you can't afford a good lawyer.
- Oh, yeah.

1879
02:16:36.564 --> 02:16:38.858
May need a good friend though.

1880
02:16:41.277 --> 02:16:44.030
I'll find you when you do. Count on it.

1881
02:16:45.865 --> 02:16:47.784
I always have.

1882
02:16:53.665 --> 02:16:57.460
<i>A full month had passed since the acquittal
and no one had made contact.</i>

1883
02:16:57.627 --> 02:16:59.713
<i>In those few weeks,
our lives reverted back…</i>

1884
02:16:59.879 --> 02:17:03.049
<i>… to what they had been
prior to the murder of Sean Nokes.</i>

1885
02:17:03.216 --> 02:17:05.885
<i>Carol had returned to her stack
of Social Service files…</i>

1886
02:17:06.052 --> 02:17:08.680
<i>… helping troubled teens
and single mothers.</i>

1887
02:17:08.847 --> 02:17:13.101
<i>John and Tommy went back to the streets,
running the West Side Boys.</i>

1888
02:17:13.268 --> 02:17:18.022
<i>I was promoted from clerk to reporter
trainee, covering the entertainment beat.</i>

1889
02:17:18.189 --> 02:17:20.525
<i>Michael, as he'd promised,
resigned from his job…</i>

1890
02:17:20.692 --> 02:17:23.361
<i>… after working the losing end
of a can't-miss case.</i>

1891
02:17:24.154 --> 02:17:25.822
Excuse me.

1892
02:17:27.991 --> 02:17:29.784
I don't know how to fucking thank you.

1893
02:17:32.829 --> 02:17:34.122
All right.

1894
02:17:34.289 --> 02:17:36.875
I can't believe what you did.
And you got away with it.

1895
02:17:37.041 --> 02:17:39.753
It wasn't me, man. That was Mikey.
It was all Mikey's plan.

1896
02:17:39.919 --> 02:17:42.630
When I heard he took the case,
I was gonna have him burned.

1897
02:17:42.797 --> 02:17:45.049
- And?
- He's a friend. If you gotta be sent away…

1898
02:17:45.216 --> 02:17:47.093
… on a murder rap, who better to do it?

1899
02:17:47.260 --> 02:17:50.138
The way he handled his case
I thought he sucked as a lawyer…

1900
02:17:50.305 --> 02:17:54.476
- … and started feeling sorry for the bastard.
- Hey, never feel sorry for a lawyer.

1901
02:17:55.435 --> 02:17:57.812
Get over here, counselor.

1902
02:17:57.979 --> 02:18:03.443
You are the real count,
alive and well and living in New York.

1903
02:18:05.028 --> 02:18:07.113
You maniac. All right, all right.

1904
02:18:07.864 --> 02:18:11.117
- You maniac. Jesus, enough.
- What, is this a gay bar?

1905
02:18:12.535 --> 02:18:14.287
It was until you came in.

1906
02:18:14.454 --> 02:18:16.790
Why don't you give me a kiss
to go with that hello?

1907
02:18:22.504 --> 02:18:24.214
Get out of the way.

1908
02:18:30.011 --> 02:18:31.846
Let's have a drink.

1909
02:18:36.643 --> 02:18:37.936
The Four Gladiators.

1910
02:18:38.102 --> 02:18:40.730
- I was trying to forget, you know?
- The Four Gladiators.

1911
02:18:40.897 --> 02:18:43.566
Worst quartet to ever hold
a Hell's Kitchen corner.

1912
02:18:43.733 --> 02:18:46.194
But what was that name
that Shakes wanted to call it?

1913
02:18:46.361 --> 02:18:49.572
No, no, genius wanted to call it
"The Count and His Cristos."

1914
02:18:49.739 --> 02:18:53.284
- Nice.
- I know, it's so sweet, isn't it?

1915
02:18:54.869 --> 02:18:58.039
We weren't that bad. I mean,
some people wanted to hear us sing.

1916
02:18:58.206 --> 02:19:00.667
Yeah, the kids at the deaf school
don't count.

1917
02:19:05.296 --> 02:19:06.422
One song for Carol.

1918
02:19:06.756 --> 02:19:08.508
- Oh, no.
- I retired a long time ago.

1919
02:19:08.675 --> 02:19:09.884
- Come on, you mutts.
- Wait.

1920
02:19:10.051 --> 02:19:12.303
Don't you guys have to go out
and shoot somebody?

1921
02:19:15.139 --> 02:19:16.599
No.

1922
02:19:17.016 --> 02:19:20.353
No, we always got time for a song.

1923
02:19:21.020 --> 02:19:22.981
Just kidding, you know what I'm saying?

1924
02:19:23.147 --> 02:19:25.441
- Wine, anybody?
- You pick it, Mike. None too slow.

1925
02:19:25.608 --> 02:19:27.694
- Let's do it right. Start us up.
- All right.

1926
02:19:31.072 --> 02:19:34.450
- How many songs did you know?
- One.

1927
02:19:39.372 --> 02:19:45.128
<i>Walk like a man</i>

1928
02:19:46.838 --> 02:19:51.092
<i>Walk like a man
Fast as you can</i>

1929
02:19:51.259 --> 02:19:54.554
<i>Walk like a man, my son</i>

1930
02:19:58.683 --> 02:20:01.394
Don't forget about the girl!

1931
02:20:14.574 --> 02:20:16.826
<i>On March 16th, 1984…</i>

1932
02:20:16.993 --> 02:20:20.496
<i>… John Reilly's bloated body was found
face-up in a tenement building…</i>

1933
02:20:20.663 --> 02:20:23.374
<i>… right next to the bottle of boiler gin
that killed him.</i>

1934
02:20:23.541 --> 02:20:27.670
<i>At the time of his death, he was a suspect
in five unsolved homicides.</i>

1935
02:20:27.837 --> 02:20:31.007
<i>He was two weeks past his 29th birthday.</i>

1936
02:20:35.094 --> 02:20:38.848
<i>Thomas Marcano died on July 26th, 1985.</i>

1937
02:20:39.015 --> 02:20:41.392
<i>He was shot at close range five times.</i>

1938
02:20:41.559 --> 02:20:44.354
<i>The body lay undiscovered
for more than a week.</i>

1939
02:20:44.520 --> 02:20:47.857
<i>There was a crucifix
and a picture of Saint Jude in his pocket.</i>

1940
02:20:48.024 --> 02:20:50.443
<i>He was 29 years old.</i>

1941
02:20:51.819 --> 02:20:54.948
<i>Michael Sullivan lives in a small town
in the English countryside…</i>

1942
02:20:55.114 --> 02:20:57.200
<i>… where he works part-time
as a carpenter.</i>

1943
02:20:57.367 --> 02:21:00.912
<i>He no longer practices law
and he has never married.</i>

1944
02:21:01.079 --> 02:21:03.665
<i>He lives quietly and alone.</i>

1945
02:21:05.708 --> 02:21:10.046
<i>Carol still works for a Social Service agency
and lives in Hell's Kitchen.</i>

1946
02:21:10.213 --> 02:21:11.714
<i>She has never married…</i>

1947
02:21:11.881 --> 02:21:15.343
<i>… but is a single mother
supporting her growing 12-year-old son.</i>

1948
02:21:15.510 --> 02:21:20.056
<i>The boy, John Thomas Michael Martinez,
loves to read…</i>

1949
02:21:20.223 --> 02:21:22.892
<i>… and is called Shakes by his mother.</i>

1950
02:21:24.894 --> 02:21:28.731
<i>It was our special night
and we held it for as long as we could.</i>

1951
02:21:28.898 --> 02:21:31.192
<i>It was our happy ending…</i>

1952
02:21:31.359 --> 02:21:33.736
<i>… and the last time we would ever
be together again.</i>

1953
02:22:23.453 --> 02:22:25.580
<i>The future lay sparkling ahead…</i>

1954
02:22:25.747 --> 02:22:28.875
<i>… and we thought we would know
each other forever.</i>

